Vaccines have helped save millions of lives. In the 19th century, before herd immunization was achieved through vaccination programs, deaths from infectious diseases, like smallpox and polio, were common. However, today, despite all the scientific evidence for their importance, vaccination programs have become somewhat controversial.

The controversy started with a paper published in 1988 and lead by Andrew Wakefield claiming there was a link between the administration of the measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine, and the appearance of autism and bowel disease. Despite much science contradicting this finding, sensationalists media reports and fear mongering from conspiracy theorists, led parts of the public to believe that vaccines were harmful. Some parents stopped vaccinating their children. This dangerous practice can be potentially disastrous given that the Center for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) estimates that vaccinations will prevent more than 21 million hospitalizations and 732,000 deaths among children born in the last 20 years (see Benefits from Immunization during the Vaccines for Children Program Era United States, 1994-2013, MMWR).

Effective communication of data is a strong antidote to misinformation and fear mongering. In this homework you are going to prepare a report to have ready in case you need to help a family member, friend or acquaintance that is not aware of the positive impact vaccines have had for public health.

The data used for these plots were collected, organized and distributed by the Tycho Project. They include weekly reported counts data for seven diseases from 1928 to 2011, from all fifty states. We include the yearly totals in the dslabs package:

Use the us_contagious_disease dataset and dplyr tools to create an object called dat that stores only the Measles data, includes a per 100,000 people rate, and removes Alaska and Hawaii since they only became states in the late 1950s. Note that there is a weeks_reporting column. Take that into account when computing the rate.
dat<-us_contagious_diseases[(us_contagious_diseases$disease=='Measles')&(us_contagious_diseases$state!='Alaska')&(us_contagious_diseases$state!='Hawaii'),]
dat<-mutate(dat,year_rate=100000*52*count/weeks_reporting/population)

  1. One problem with the boxplot is that it does not let us see state-specific trends. Make a plot showing the trends for all states. Add the US average to the plot. The US average line is the average across states for each year. You will need to calculate this yourself, being careful to take into account state populations. There will be a different value for each year. Then, add the average trendline to your plot using a separate layer. Hint: Note there are missing values in the data.
usaverage<-data.frame(yearr=c(1928:2002))
for (i in usaverage$yearr) {
  wanted <- dat %>% filter(year==i & !is.na(year_rate))
  usaverage$rate[i-1927]=sum(wanted$year_rate*wanted$population)/sum(wanted$population)
}

#We use a black line on the top layer to represent the average rate in US each year.
ggplot() +
     geom_line(data=na.omit(dat),aes(year,year_rate,color=state)) +
     scale_y_continuous(trans="sqrt",breaks=(c(4,16,36,64,100,400,1000))) +
     xlab("Year") +
     ylab("Cases per 100,000 person-year") +
     ggtitle("Measles spread rate across states") +
     geom_vline(xintercept = 1963, lty = 2, color="blue") +
     geom_line(data=usaverage,aes(x=yearr,y=rate),color="black")

The data describes the prevalence of autism among groups of people born in each year from 1931 to 2014 in California. Its obtained from the supplementary information of the paper by Nevison et al.

We can observe that the prevalence of autism gradually rises from nearly zero among people born in 1931 to almost 120 cases per 10,000 people among those born in 2012 (note that the drop in prevalence in 2013/14 is mainly due to the fact that many people born in both years havent developed autism or got diagnosed yet). I wouldnt say that the increase in autism prevalence coincided with the introduction of measles vaccine because the slope of the autism prevalence curve got significantly much larger at around 1980s, almost 20 years after measles vaccine introduction. I would rather propose that some other factors promoted the rise of autism, like changes in the social and physical environment in which children grew up.

Reference: Nevison, C., Blaxill, M. & Zahorodny, W. (2018) California Autism Prevalence Trends from 1931 to 2014 and Comparison to National ASD Data from IDEA and ADDM. J Autism Dev Disord, 48(12): 41034117.

We see that there are 6 other diseases besides measles. Since the data for pertussis and polio get mixed up and smallpox vaccine was introduced really early in the 18th century, we wont be including these diseases. Also, the vaccine for mumps was introduced before the start time of mumps data so mumps is excluded as well. Thus, we will be only discussing the effects of vaccine on hepatitis A and rubella.

hdat %>% ggplot(aes(year, state,  fill = year_rate)) +

The vaccines of hepatitis A and rubella were first introduced in 1995 and 1969, respectively. From the geom tile plots we can see that both vaccines seem to decrease the prevalence of disease, yet the effects are both small (hard to discern). For hepatitis A, the reason is that the spread rate was already low in many states so the change is not pronounced; for rubella, the reason is that there are too many missing values before vaccine introduction to make a solid comparison.

The boxplots offer us further information. We can see that hepatitis A prevalence didnt go down at the time of vaccine introduction until several years later, whereas we observe a rather quick decrease in the prevalence of rubella following vaccine introduction. Therefore, we conclude that there was an immediate benefit from rubella vaccine but the benefits from hepatitis A vaccine was lagging. As for mumps, pertussis, polio and smallpox, there arent enough data to explore the effects of vaccines.
